# Hardware Projects

I work with computers every day. Writing Software. Usually, I use a high level language like Java or Scala, which provides a lot of abstraction over the hardware. Occasionally, I like to delve deeper into the stack, and work on something closer to the electrons of the device.

I don't have a background in hardware. Beyond A-Level physics and a module on computer architecture during my degree, I have never studied hardware. That doesn't stop it being fascinating. The way that you can make a physical device interact with something seemingly ephemeral. The tangible and the intangible. Working as one to do something you want.

My dad is an electrician, so I suppose it's not surprising that I have at least a passing interest in electrics and electronics. In fact, my first taste of electrics was getting a basic qualification from a summer school held by my local college in electrics and plumbing. Maybe that set me on a path of having a causal interest?

Over the years, I've played around with a few pet projects here and there. I'll go into them in more detail in other blog posts, but some of the highlights include:

## My Internet Connected Lamp
A strange purchase from eBay, an old railway signal head. It has a red and green lamp, plus 'pigs ears'. Naturally, I had to put a Raspberry Pi into it to implement a new version of [HTTP 418](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Status/418)'s teapot protocol - the lamp protocol.

![Green Aspect](data:image/png;base64,)

#### [Read more about my Internet Connected Railway Signal Lamp](2016-archive-internet-connected-lamp)

## Raspberry Pi Thermometer
I've been in several offices where it's warm, perhaps too warm, but without having the data to back that statement up. So, I built a device to collect the data to back me up!

![thermometer](data:image/png;base64,)

#### [Read more about the Raspberry Pi Thermometer](2014-archive-raspberry-pi-thermometer)

## Bicycle Computer
I am sure many of you will have heard of [Garmin](https://explore.garmin.com/en-GB/cycling/) or [Fitbit](https://www.fitbit.com/uk/home), who make fitness trackers. As you go further into the rabbit hole of sports technology, you get to cycle computers. I tried making one of my own, and the conclusion: Epic respect to the people that design the one I actually use!

![various components](data:image/png;base64,)

#### [Read More about my bicyle computer project](2014-archive-a-bicycle-computer-in-several-parts)

## Train simulator controller
A few years ago, at the [London Transport Museum](https://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/)'s [Acton Depot](https://www.ltmuseum.co.uk/visit/museum-depot)'s open day, I came across a dead mans handle for sale. Naturally I purchased it, but I didn't have a clue what to do with it. Fast forward a few years, and some advances in Arduino technology, and I turned it into a game controller for playing train simulators!


![handles](data:image/png;base64,)


#### [Read more about the Train Simulator Controller](2016-archive-train-simulator-controller)

## Onwards and upwards...
Nowadays, hardware has taken a bit of a back seat. It's still fun to play around with, but as with everyone, my interests have shifted slightly into other areas. Maybe I will come back to it one day...
